Bananas Foster French toast and sweet potato pancakes are a must at this institution! Wonderful way to start your day!!

The food is good. Dont get me wrong, but the fact that its packed and it takes about an hour or even two to get your food is so not worth the wait.. The service is not even that great either. 2 stars.

The name says it all! This is one of the cuisines I wish we had more of in SoCal so imagine how ecstatic I was to try this place out. We were forewarned about the wait and luckily, we came on a weekday at an odd time for lunch. No wait! They serve their brunch menu only until 3PM and we got here just in the nick of time. As long as you get seated before 3 then you're okay. They have an afternoon menu which is quite limited so make sure to come early. We started off with their CRAWFISH BEIGNETS ($8). Plan to share because a plate consists of three and they're pretty filling. The dough is completely covered with cayenne powder which was a bit much if you ask me. It sure added that kick but it wasn't as spicy as it looked. The filling had cheddar cheese, scallions, and plenty of crawfish meat which I really enjoyed. A-must! SHRIMP & GRITS ($12) seemed to be a hit here so it was something I had to order. Verdict? It definitely lived up to the hype! One of the best cheddar grits I've had to date. It's very filling! The sauteed shrimps and spicy tomato-bacon gravy made this bowl so rich in flavor. It's awesome! We also got the BFC (Buttermilk Fried Chicken-Southern Style) ($12.75) which came with french fries, a biscuit, and a side of coleslaw. This was our least favorite on the table. The chicken pieces were so sad-looking and tasted disappointing. The biscuit on the other hand was delicious and their coleslaw was amazing. I'll give them that. I had a few bites of the FRIED CATFISH BENEDICT ($11.75) which my sister ordered. This came with a side of cheddar grits. In theory it would have been a great dish but their flavorful biscuit masked the catfish in taste while the texture of both the biscuit and fish were very similar. It was begging for some crunch or alternative mouth-feel. Don't get me wrong, each component was delicious, they just didn't work together for me. Meanwhile, the side of cheddar grits has a more subtle flavor compared to the grits the shrimp came with. Sans the tomato-bacon gravy, you'd think it wouldn't be as good but I still loved it! It was scrumptious! We ordered the CHICKEN ETOUFFEE ($10) thinking our food was not enough. It turned out we had to take half of it home as we were already too full. They didn't skimp out on the meat here but I wish it had enough rice to balance it out. In my opinion, this tasted better the next day when all the creole flavors from the tomato gravy got absorbed by the chicken and rice. Don't forget to order their WATERMELON TEA ($2.75). It's the perfect thirst-quencher to a soulful meal you'll be getting here. Better yet, it's refillable! SERVICE is quick and friendly. Can't complain! Street parking only so bring quarters. Would I come back? If I'm in town, oh yes!!!

My husband got the famous hangtown and it tasted way too fishy. So beware of having that for breakfast if that's not your thing. I got the shrimp and goat cheese omelette. It had wayyyyy more caramelized onions than shrimp and goat cheese. I would've preferred a better balance. I ended up opening it up and eating the shrimp and goat cheese (which were very good together). The saving grace for us was the AMAZINGLY DELICIOUS grits and biscuit! We would come back for them. Yum!

Oh Brenda, you make my heart melt. Wait time here can be a pain. I came during Christmas week on a weekday and the wait was about 30 minutes. The beignets are soooooo good! I mean, I can eat it all day, everyday. The fried chicken was crunchy and moist. Flavor wise, I want to say I've had better, but this will do. The biscuits are off the hook! I'm not a biscuit fan, but these are soft and fluffy (like me) Everything is reasonable priced, the dining area is great with the skylight, but keep in mind, if its super packed, its really loud. Parking is horrible around here, so either be prepared to circle around or take an Uber.

The Crawfish Beignets. The reason to come and try this place. Also enjoyed the vegetarian omelette, great grits, biscuit lacked the creole touch, egg benedict with chicken worked a charm. Worth a brunch.

Yesterday was officially my last day of work with the State of California, DIR-DWC, located at 455 Golden Gate Avenue, 2nd Floor. It was also my first time dining at Brenda's French Soul Food. I always wanted to dine here, but somehow the stars were never aligned at the right time to allow me to do so. Many times I have walked passed Brenda's, heading to KFC for their chicken pot pie or to Walgreen's on Eddy and Van Ness. Then there were times that I would stop short of Brenda's and get my lunch at Street Eats. A friend of mine who has the twinkling of stars in her eyes and a personality of star quality treated me to lunch at Brenda's and all I can say is God bless her for her kindness. I have her and another fellow yelper (Ray R) to thank for their reviews. There were so many wonderful descriptions of the food being offered on the menu that I did not know which item I wanted to try first. Since I haven't had hush puppies in over seven years ago, that was a must try with the remoulade. Do I want the BFC (Brenda's fried chicken) lunch entree or shall I go with the Chicken Etouffee (shredded chicken in a spicy tomato gravy and rice)? I have eaten fried chicken from different places...let me be adventurous and daring...I have never had etouffee, so Chicken Etouffee it is. My friend decided on the Hangtown Fry (oysters, bacon, scallion scramble) with cheese grits and cream biscuit. She also recommended the beignet flight for dessert, as her favorite was beignet with ganache...mmm...I had beignet with fresh strawberries and ganache at another venue...so sinfully delish...enough to have me drooling...lol. The beignet flight consisted of four different beignets - plain, chocolate, apple and crawfish. Oh yes - another must have because I was very eager to taste the wonderful, savory crawfish beignet - dusted with cayenne pepper. The restaurant was crowded and one can just imagine the noise level...pretty loud and somewhat hard to carry on a conversation, but it was all good. Though the wait for our food took a while, it was understandable with many people dining at about the same time - lunch time. Then, I wasn't going to get upset at our waiter because one of the hush puppies fell off the plate and landed on the table - no big deal. My sense of humor had me doing something "cray, cray"...I held that hush puppy, raised my hand up and rapped on "oh yeah, wave it in the air like I don't care...whoot, whoot, whoot...God created dirt and dirt don't hurt"...hey, hey...lol. The food was great, the service a tad slow, the ambiance was fine and I was totally impressed for quite an enjoyable dining experience. What else can I say...it was my first (in Brenda's), my last (day in the office) and my everything (that I expected) from Brenda's. I know it sounds like I'm putting a little of the late Barry White in this, but when I hear old school music being played up in the place, hey I gotta go there...lol. There will be returned trips and the next time I am bringing my husband along for them crawfish beignets and the shrimp po boy sandwiches. Oh yummy - I can hardly wait!! Finally, again my friend, thank you for your friendship, kindness and gift, which I will treasure for many years.

Came here with my parents for dinner on a Saturday night after seeing my mom's pictures on facebook the previous month (LOL). We came in at around 6 and the wait was only about 10 minutes? Pretty good considering I heard people wait for longer usually! I got to try the crawfish beignet, the shrimp and grits, and the kingcake beignet (mardi gras special) and the watermelon tea. Crawfish beignet: Sososoo good. When you cut into it, you can see how hot it is and the crawfish filling starts to ooze out. It gets a little spicy after a while, but nothing I couldn't handle! This was definitely filling, just being the first part of my meal. Maybe split this and an entree with one other person if you're not a big eater! Shrimp and grits: Wow. This was my first time having grits and I was a little confused as to what exactly it was, but nonetheless I definitely enjoyed it! I loved the cheesy topping and the shrimp were also pretty big, and they gave a decent amount too! Would order again! Kingcake beignet: Wasn't sure what to expect with this because i'm not exactly informed about mardi gras culture, but it was delicious! Inside was a berry compote and it was really good with the breadiness (not a word... oh well) from the beignet. it also came with a baby jesus on top (when we ordered, my dad and I were so confused about this... was it edible? is it sprinkles? what? turned out it was a plastic baby jesus figure stuck on top of the beignet). I want to try the normal beignets next time! Watermelon tea: This was pretty good! The watermelon flavor is VERY true to the actual fruit which I loved. Also, FREE REFILLS!! Who doesn't love free?! I def recommend this restaurant to anyone! :)

This was my second time at Brenda's. The crawfish beignets are what brought me back! We went in on Wed night for dinner around 6:30pm. The WAIT TIME wasn't long at all. We put our name on the board for 2, and were seated pretty quickly--I'd say within 30 minutes. I remember the CRAWFISH BEIGNETS being a-maz-ing and full of crawfish. Same concept, so it took away some of the flavor. The SHRIMP & GRITS were great! If you like cheese, you'll want to order this. It was a warm, hearty serving of grits smothered in cheese, topped off with sauteed shrimp and perfectly seasoned tomatoes. This time around, I also ordered the OYSTER FLIGHT. The Tchoupitoulas with cayenne was super spicy for me since I'm a spice wimp, but still cooked well. Wasn't a fan of the BBQ one at all (the Orleans). The Casino had great flavor and the biscuit on top was nice and crispy. Although they weren't awful, I don't think I'd order them again. As for the SERVICE, the server was amazing! Very friendly, attentive, and accommodating. The entire atmosphere felt warm and inviting, including the guests. This is a great spot for a relaxed dinner with one or two friends. I'm sure I'll be back again.

Now for the parking, it can be difficult to find a parking spot, but that is expected because of the density of San Francisco. When we came back we still had to wait another 20 mins before they called our name. Once we sat down ordering and getting our food didn't take too long since the waiters/waitresses are hustling non stop! If you plan on trying this place out I would suggest to be outside as soon as they open or be prepared to wait a while. Do yourself a favor and try those crawfish beignets, you won't regret it!

    The name says it all! This is one of the cuisines I wish we had more of in SoCal so imagine how ecstatic I was to try this place out.

    We were forewarned about the wait and luckily, we came on a weekday at an odd time for lunch. No wait! They serve their brunch menu only until 3PM and we got here just in the nick of time. As long as you get seated before 3 then you're okay. They have an afternoon menu which is quite limited so make sure to come early.

    We started off with their CRAWFISH BEIGNETS ($8). Plan to share because a plate consists of three and they're pretty filling. The dough is completely covered with cayenne powder which was a bit much if you ask me. It sure added that kick but it wasn't as spicy as it looked. The filling had cheddar cheese, scallions, and plenty of crawfish meat which I really enjoyed. A-must!

    SHRIMP & GRITS ($12) seemed to be a hit here so it was something I had to order. Verdict? It definitely lived up to the hype! One of the best cheddar grits I've had to date. It's very filling! The sauteed shrimps and spicy tomato-bacon gravy made this bowl so rich in flavor. It's awesome!

    We also got the BFC (Buttermilk Fried Chicken-Southern Style) ($12.75) which came with french fries, a biscuit, and a side of coleslaw. This was our least favorite on the table. The chicken pieces were so sad-looking and tasted disappointing. The biscuit on the other hand was delicious and their coleslaw was amazing. I'll give them that.

    I had a few bites of the FRIED CATFISH BENEDICT ($11.75) which my sister ordered. This came with a side of cheddar grits. In theory it would have been a great dish but their flavorful biscuit masked the catfish in taste while the texture of both the biscuit and fish were very similar. It was begging for some crunch or alternative mouth-feel. Don't get me wrong, each component was delicious, they just didn't work together for me. Meanwhile, the side of cheddar grits has a more subtle flavor compared to the grits the shrimp came with. Sans the tomato-bacon gravy, you'd think it wouldn't be as good but I still loved it! It was scrumptious!

    We ordered the CHICKEN ETOUFFEE ($10) thinking our food was not enough. It turned out we had to take half of it home as we were already too full. They didn't skimp out on the meat here but I wish it had enough rice to balance it out. In my opinion, this tasted better the next day when all the creole flavors from the tomato gravy got absorbed by the chicken and rice.

    Don't forget to order their WATERMELON TEA ($2.75). It's the perfect thirst-quencher to a soulful meal you'll be getting here. Better yet, it's refillable!

    SERVICE is quick and friendly. Can't complain! Street parking only so bring quarters.

    Would I come back? If I'm in town, oh yes!!!

    Came here with my parents for dinner on a Saturday night after seeing my mom's pictures on facebook the previous month (LOL). We came in at around 6 and the wait was only about 10 minutes? Pretty good considering I heard people wait for longer usually!

    I got to try the crawfish beignet, the shrimp and grits, and the kingcake beignet (mardi gras special) and the watermelon tea.

    Crawfish beignet: Sososoo good. When you cut into it, you can see how hot it is and the crawfish filling starts to ooze out. It gets a little spicy after a while, but nothing I couldn't handle! This was definitely filling, just being the first part of my meal. Maybe split this and an entree with one other person if you're not a big eater!

    Shrimp and grits: Wow. This was my first time having grits and I was a little confused as to what exactly it was, but nonetheless I definitely enjoyed it! I loved the cheesy topping and the shrimp were also pretty big, and they gave a decent amount too! Would order again!

    Kingcake beignet: Wasn't sure what to expect with this because i'm not exactly informed about mardi gras culture, but it was delicious! Inside was a berry compote and it was really good with the breadiness (not a word... oh well) from the beignet. it also came with a baby jesus on top (when we ordered, my dad and I were so confused about this... was it edible? is it sprinkles? what? turned out it was a plastic baby jesus figure stuck on top of the beignet). I want to try the normal beignets next time!

    Watermelon tea: This was pretty good! The watermelon flavor is VERY true to the actual fruit which I loved. Also, FREE REFILLS!! Who doesn't love free?!

    I def recommend this restaurant to anyone! :)

    This was my second time at Brenda's. The crawfish beignets are what brought me back!

    We went in on Wed night for dinner around 6:30pm. The WAIT TIME wasn't long at all. We put our name on the board for 2, and were seated pretty quickly--I'd say within 30 minutes.

    I remember the CRAWFISH BEIGNETS being a-maz-ing and full of crawfish. Unfortunately, this time around, they were mostly dough. Don't get me wrong, the dough is soft and delish, but I was hoping for more filling than what we had. It was like when you get a jelly-filled donut and there is only dime size squeeze of jelly in the center. You have to spread that jelly thin to get some in every bite. Same concept, so it took away some of the flavor.

    The SHRIMP & GRITS were great! If you like cheese, you'll want to order this. It was a warm, hearty serving of grits smothered in cheese, topped off with sauteed shrimp and perfectly seasoned tomatoes.

    This time around, I also ordered the OYSTER FLIGHT. The Tchoupitoulas with cayenne was super spicy for me since I'm a spice wimp, but still cooked well. Wasn't a fan of the BBQ one at all (the Orleans). The Casino had great flavor and the biscuit on top was nice and crispy. Although they weren't awful, I don't think I'd order them again.

    As for the SERVICE, the server was amazing! Very friendly, attentive, and accommodating. The entire atmosphere felt warm and inviting, including the guests. This is a great spot for a relaxed dinner with one or two friends. I'm sure I'll be back again.

    This is probably my 10th time coming here, and it won't be my last! I love this restaurant because the price is affordable for the type of style of food that is offered along with the huge portion. I initially wanted to get the Fried Chicken Eggs Benedict which is the usual thing I order from there since it is 10/10 of goodness in my book, but to my disappointment, I found out that the restaurant only serves that during the weekend! Therefore, this is just a precaution information if you are going there to try the Fried Chicken Eggs Benedict.

    For today, I ordered the Hangtown Fry with biscuit and hash which I'm glad to have ordered. I'm glad that this restaurant is not skimpy with their seafood quantity in meals like typical restaurants because the scallion scramble has a ton of fried oyster; this scallion scramble has a bunch of bacon as well.

    Aside from the Hangtown Fry, I must recommend to anyone to order the Crawfish Beignets because this is essentially the main reason why I come to this restaurant. It is one of the best thing that I have ever eaten because there's a ton of crawfish in it along with cheese, and on the outside, it's sprinkled with some Cajun seasoning that is topped with green onion; an order comes with three beignets. As I observe the restaurant, I always see people eating the Crawfish Beignets or the dessert beignets (plain, apple, or chocolate), so I know I'm not the only person that loves these beignets.

    Now for the parking, it can be difficult to find a parking spot, but that is expected because of the density of San Francisco. So is it worth the trouble of finding a parking spot to try this restaurant? YES! Therefore, come to this place when you're in the Bay Area!

    Two words, CRAWFISH BEIGNETS. So freaking delicious! I think usually if you want the Crawfish beignets you have to get the order of 3 but our waiter was nice enough to let my bf and I get one only since we were going to get other dishes. I got the shrimp and grits and really enjoyed it! The only thing I didn't like was the tomato in it but I'm just not a fan of tomatoes in general. The shrimp and grits also had bacon bits which made the dish even better. Bf got the fried chicken eggs Benedict and loved most of it. He did mention the grits were too buttery for his liking but he really enjoyed everything else!

    Brenda's French Soul Food is super busy so be ready for a long wait. When we arrived there was a huge crowd waiting basically up and down the block. You have to go in and write your name down in the huge chalk board that they have. The restaurant itself is not very big so there's no space to be able to wait inside. We had a looooong list in front of us so we went to walk around the area for about 40 mins to kill some time. When we came back we still had to wait another 20 mins before they called our name. Once we sat down ordering and getting our food didn't take too long since the waiters/waitresses are hustling non stop!

    If you plan on trying this place out I would suggest to be outside as soon as they open or be prepared to wait a while. Do yourself a favor and try those crawfish beignets, you won't regret it!
